Expanding $(x-2)^2$ gives $1<x^2-4x+4<25$.  Rearranging the inequality, we have $0<x^2-4x+3<24$.  Factoring the quadratic, we get $(x-3)(x-1)<24$.  We can now solve for $x$ by considering the two cases: \begin{align*}
(x-3)(x-1)&<24\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-3<0\text{ and } x-1&>\frac{-24}{x-3}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x<3\text{ and } x&>3-\frac{24}{x-3}
\end{align*}or \begin{align*}
(x-3)(x-1)&<24\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x-3>0\text{ and } x-1&<\frac{-24}{x-3}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x>3\text{ and } x&<3-\frac{24}{x-3}.
\end{align*}Simplifying the second inequality in each case gives $x<7$ and $x>-\frac{5}{3}$, respectively.  Therefore, the solutions are $x=-2,-1,0,1,2,3,4,5,6$, and their sum is $\boxed{18}$.

